                        </a></div></div><ol class="sense_single" htag="ol"><li class="sense" htag="li" id="accidence_sng_1" hclass="sense"><span class="sensetop" htag="span" hclass="sensetop"><span class="def" htag="span" hclass="def">the part of grammar that deals with the <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/inflection#inflection_topg_1" title="inflections definition"><span class="ndv">inflections</span></a> of words <span class="gloss" htag="span" hclass="gloss">(= changes in their form according to their function in the sentence)</span></span></span><div class="collapse" hclass="collapse" htag="div"><span class="unbox" id="accidence_unbox_1" unbox="wordorigin"><span class="box_title">Word Origin</span><span class="body"><span class="p">early 16th cent.: from late Latin <span class="ei">accidentia</span> (translation of Greek <span class="ei">parepomena</span> ‘things happening alongside’), neuter plural of the present participle of <span class="ei">accidere</span> ‘happen’ from <span class="ei">ad-</span> ‘towards, to’ + <span class="ei">cadere</span> ‘to fall’.</span></span></span></div>    <div id="ring-links-box">
